Section 1: Loading the libraries

Overall Research Question:

What is the impact of various lifestyle choices on sleep quality among adults?

Introduction to the data set.

The data set utilized for this work was obtained from Kaggle, a website and collection of services for data science, including dataset hosting. The data set license is under the Authors, listed as Equilibrium, but the datas source was not available. Regardless, the data set is highly rated and widely used for academic purposes.

  • Analysis of the data encountered:

The data set provides comprehensive information on sleep quality and related factors for 452 individuals. The data set includes demographic information such as age (9-69 years), and gender. Detailed sleep metrics recorded include bedtime, waketime, total sleep duration, number of awakenings during the night and sleep efficiency. Additionally, the dataset measures the percentage of sleep spent in different stages: REM, deep, and light sleep. The Sleep efficiency feature is a measure of the proportion of time spent asleep in bed.

Beyond sleep-specific data, the dataset captures lifestyle factors that influence sleep quality. These factors include caffeine/alcohol consumption, smoking status, and exercise frequency. Overall, this dataset is well-suited for investigating the relationships between sleep quality and various demographic and lifestyle factors, offering insights into how behaviors and characteristics impact sleep patterns and efficiency.

The table above summarises important information about the variables.

Gender Sleep Efficiency, Sleep Duration and excercise Frequency variables: By Eduard Vargas

Research Questions:

In order to understand the data a sleeping efficiency, which was defined by the author as A measure of the proportion of time spent in bed that is actually spent asleep., I decided to use a simple linear regression model in order to find the relationships between the habits of an adult person, and the consequences on the mentioned sleeping efficiency.

Here, the intercept, or dependent variable will be Sleep Efficiency:

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Sleep.efficiency ~ Age + Caffeine.consumption + 
##     Alcohol.consumption + Exercise.frequency + Gender, data = cleaned_data)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -0.32074 -0.07276  0.01985  0.07990  0.27445 
## 
## Coefficients:

## (Intercept)           0.7184739  0.0221180  32.484  < 2e-16 ***
## Age                   0.0016640  0.0004670   3.563 0.000413 ***
## Caffeine.consumption  0.0002822  0.0002164   1.304 0.193129    
## Alcohol.consumption  -0.0336521  0.0037310  -9.020  < 2e-16 ***
## Exercise.frequency    0.0261673  0.0042395   6.172 1.72e-09 ***
## GenderMale           -0.0219210  0.0130756  -1.676 0.094462 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.1176 on 382 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2584, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2487 
## F-statistic: 26.62 on 5 and 382 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Observations:

The linear model analysis reveals several significant relationships between the predictors and sleep efficiency. The model explains about 25.84% of the variability in sleep efficiency (R-squared = 0.2584). Key predictors such as age, alcohol consumption, and exercise frequency have significant effects on sleep efficiency, while caffeine consumption is not a significant predictor. The intercept indicates the baseline sleep efficiency when all predictors are at zero, and the overall model is statistically significant (p-value < 2.2e-16).

Specific Observations:

  • Gender: Coefficient for Gender (Male): -0.0219210 Interpretation: On average, males have a sleep efficiency that is approximately 2.19% lower than females, although this effect is only marginally significant (p = 0.094462). Significance: The marginal significance suggests that while there is a difference in sleep efficiency between genders, it is not as strongly supported by the data compared to other predictors.

  • Exercise Frequency Coefficient for Exercise Frequency: 0.0261673

Interpretation: Each additional day of exercise per week is associated with a 2.62% increase in sleep efficiency, holding other factors constant.

Significance: This relationship is highly significant (p = 1.72e-09), indicating a strong positive impact of exercise on sleep efficiency.

Summary: The linear model highlights that while gender has a marginal impact on sleep efficiency, exercise frequency has a robust positive effect. These insights can inform strategies to improve sleep quality, particularly emphasizing the benefits of regular exercise.

After understanding the relevant variables that affect the Sleeping Efficiency it is important to visualize how the current information is, and then proceed to work on more relationships with the help of the model elaborated:

First of all, it is important to understand what is the average exercise level and reported sleeping quality per gender:

Observations from the table:

After organizing the data, it is evident that despite males reporting higher sleep efficiency, females actually exhibit higher average sleep quality with less average exercise per week. This discrepancy could be associated with gender-related perceptions or ego, which do not reflect the actual evidence. The data suggests that females maintain better sleep efficiency with fewer exercise sessions compared to their male counterparts, highlighting an interesting dynamic in sleep quality assessments between genders.

In the following section, I will plot and visualize the relationships between exercise frequency, duration and sleep efficiency. To identify possible trends in sleep efficiency levels, in order to examine the distribution, I will make use of histogram and scatter plots. These visualizations will help in understanding how exercise frequency influences sleep efficiency and whether consistent patterns emerge across different levels of physical activity.

Sleep Efficiency and Exercise Frequency per Gender:

Both the dot plot and the histogram display the distribution of sleep efficiency by exercise frequency and gender, revealing several important observations:

  1. The general shape of the distribution indicates that sleep efficiency tends to skew towards higher values, with many individuals exhibiting sleep efficiencies closer to 1.0. This suggests that a significant portion of the population enjoys high sleep efficiency. Additionally, a positive relationship between exercise frequency and sleep efficiency is apparent, particularly noticeable at exercise frequencies of 3 and 5 days per week, implying that regular exercise may contribute to better sleep efficiency.

  2. Breaking down the data by exercise frequency, we observe varied patterns for different levels of physical activity. For individuals who do not exercise at all (0 days), both males and females show a wide range of sleep efficiencies, with some clustering at lower efficiencies (around 0.6) and others at higher efficiencies (0.9 to 1.0). As exercise frequency increases to 1 and 2 days per week, the concentration of individuals with sleep efficiencies around 0.8 to 1.0 becomes more pronounced, although fewer individuals exercise only 2 days per week. For those exercising 3 days per week, there is a notable peak in high sleep efficiency, especially among males. The trend of high sleep efficiency continues for those exercising 4 and 5 days per week, despite the lower number of individuals in these categories.

  3. When comparing genders, both males and females exhibit a trend of higher sleep efficiency with increased exercise frequency. Females tend to have a more evenly spread distribution across different exercise levels but consistently show high sleep efficiency. Males, on the other hand, display a stronger concentration at higher sleep efficiencies, particularly at higher levels of exercise frequency. Overall, the data suggests that regular exercise, particularly at moderate to high levels (3-5 days a week), is associated with better sleep efficiency for both genders, reinforcing the benefits of physical activity on sleep quality.

Sleep Duration, Efficiency and the relationship with Exercise Frequency per Gender:

Observations on the plots:

These two visualizations provide a detailed analysis of the relationship between sleep duration, sleep efficiency, exercise frequency, and gender:

  1. On the scatter plots at the top, for females, sleep efficiency generally remains high, above 0.8, across various sleep durations, with a noticeable concentration around 7 to 8 hours. They also indicate that a significant number of females maintain high sleep efficiency regardless of their exact sleep duration within this range. Similarly, for males, sleep efficiency is also predominantly high, though there is slightly more variability compared to females. Males exhibit a similar pattern of maintaining high sleep efficiency across different sleep durations, particularly between 6 and 9 hours.

  2. The histograms at the bottom show the distribution of sleep duration across different exercise frequencies, comparing males and females. For individuals who do not exercise at all (0 days), both genders exhibit a concentration of sleep durations around 7 to 8 hours, with females showing a slightly higher count. This pattern is consistent for low exercise frequency (1 day), where the distribution is quite balanced between genders. As exercise frequency increases to moderate levels (2 days), there are fewer data points, but the trend of sleep durations around 7 to 8 hours continues, particularly for females. For moderate to high exercise frequencies (3 days), males show a higher count of sleep durations around 7 to 8 hours compared to females. For high (4 days) and very high exercise frequencies (5 days), the data is sparse, but the clustering around 7 to 8 hours persists, with a slight balance between males and females.

  3. Overall, the scatter plots suggest that both males and females maintain high sleep efficiency (above 0.8) across various sleep durations, particularly between 6 and 9 hours. The histograms indicate that regardless of exercise frequency, both genders tend to have a similar distribution of sleep durations, predominantly around 7 to 8 hours. These observations highlight that regular exercise does not significantly alter the preferred sleep duration but suggests a tendency towards maintaining high sleep efficiency within these durations. The consistency across genders and exercise frequencies underscores the importance of sleep duration in achieving optimal sleep efficiency, suggesting that individuals may achieve better sleep quality by focusing on maintaining a consistent sleep duration.

General conclusions:

The analysis of sleep efficiency in relation to exercise frequency and gender reveals that a significant portion of the population enjoys high sleep efficiency, particularly as exercise frequency increases. The distribution indicates that many individuals exhibit sleep efficiencies closer to 1.0, with a positive relationship between exercise frequency and sleep efficiency becoming evident, especially at frequencies of 3 and 5 days per week. This trend implies that regular exercise contributes to better sleep efficiency, reinforcing the benefits of physical activity on sleep quality. Notably, individuals who exercise more frequently tend to maintain higher sleep efficiency, highlighting the importance of an active lifestyle for achieving optimal sleep.

Further examination of the data reveals distinct patterns based on gender and exercise frequency. Both males and females show higher sleep efficiency with increased exercise, although the distribution patterns vary slightly. Females tend to have a more evenly spread distribution across different exercise levels, while males display a stronger concentration of higher sleep efficiencies, particularly at higher exercise frequencies. Regardless of exercise frequency, both genders exhibit a consistent sleep duration, predominantly around 7 to 8 hours, suggesting that exercise does not significantly alter the preferred sleep duration but enhances sleep efficiency within this range. These observations suggest that individuals may achieve better sleep quality by focusing on regular exercise and maintaining a consistent sleep duration.

This proves the significant correlation shown by the linear model at the beginning of this work.

Conclusion:

Using regression, Adrian found a weaker than expected link between age, alcohol consumption and several measures of sleep quality.

When comparing variables against sleep efficiency, Age seemed to have a more significant positive effect between 29-59. Alcohol seemed to have a more significant effect than regression indicated, though its influence peaked at a middling dose. He also identified a very weak moderation effect between age and alcohol consumption.
